	<tr>
	
		<td class="msg_user_cell" width="150" valign=top>
		
			 









<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=35383'  class="auth_text"  style="font-weight:bold;" >	
<span style='color:#336600;'>Mookse</span></a>
			<br>
			
			<span style="font-size: 8pt;">
			Journeyman<br>
			
				Posts: 72<br>
				
				Registered: 05-19-2004
				
			</span>
			


			
			<br>
			
				<img src="/i/p.gif" height=8 width=150 border=0 alt=""><br>
				
			<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=35383'>







</a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=PVP&message.id=1276#M1276">102</a> of 128
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 499 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			Although I certainly like a lot of what people have been saying here, I think the foundational strategem is misguided.  Much of what has been discussed has actually already been tried at what time or another.  The problem seems to lie at two strange poles.<br><br>Either there was too much intervention from Verant/Sony or there was too little.  Item Loot and faction loss were both eliminated from the Kunark worlds because people didn't like it.  Rather than pose challenges, Verant acquiesced, and removed the procedure from both team servers.  They 'listened' to their player base who wanted things easier.  Then things got abandoned, and no attention was paid to the rulesets of the Zeks.  Players felt that it would be more sensible for them to bypass the team structures, and did so without recrimination.<br><br>The difficulty for the devs, is to create a world and stick to its consequences unfailingly.  Now we have little left to cling to, and the only 'rules' in place are disregarded and exploited (immy healing , cross-team training, etc).  In my more frustrated moments, it seems fair for the devs to pack up and go and burn all the Zek servers in an outdoor bonfire... I really can't imagine anyone denying that EQ's strength lies entirely in it's PvE, so at these times I feel it's best for us to stop griping, and enjoy the game for what it's good at, not it's ineffectual tangents.  If you want PvP go to DaoC.  You'll never see consequential PvE again, (/Austin Powers on) but if that's your bag, man...<br><br>Such a server as suggested here, would have an extremely small following.  I don't see a lot of time-seasoned adventurers wanting to re-live the hours waiting for boats to travel a continent to get some violence on... or just to get to mainland Antonica for that matter (/shiver).  It was an erstwhile shot, but the only thing that can re-invigorate PvP, if it's even possible, is to turn players' worlds upside down every once in a while, where the playstyles of the 'rich' and 'powerful' are turned on end, and they suddenly see themselves as the under-dog and have to actually fight to regain what they've lost.  This is one of the reasons I would love to see the Team-Servers be hard-coded as such... all the ueber X-team Guilds would now be ineffectual, and players would need to re-orient themselves to the 'new' (rofl) environment.  This sort of cataclysmic upheaval is the only thing that inspires hope and anger.  Imagine the struggles in trying to recoup, regroup, and re-strategize to become effectual again.  And when things settle down... OOPS!  Time to turn the tables again, and watch the beautiful scrabbling unfold.<br><br>A good PvP world is one where there is a fight against the unknown as well as the well-trodden.  If all you want to do is placate the high-end gamer, you do not have a PvP server, you have a domesticated and ruling endowed elite that cannot be unseated.  That, alas, doesn't make for particularly good PvP.  If there is nothing to be gained from rebellion, no one will do it.  If there is no threat to the power structure, they will languish in their strength, and seek to inflict their whims upon others without fear of any retribution for their actions.  This is a gankfest and this is grief, and it sounds a lot like SZ, or what the other servers will become with GvG.  GvG does NOT promote novelty, it is a reward for exploitation, and there remains no challengers to the high-end guilds... no more so than there is now, at any rate.<br><br>I suspect Sony hasn't given any of this any thought, and would be far more loathe to anger high-end sediment than to upset those muddied waters that would give everyone reason to fight again.<br><br>Love,<br><br>Zimz	
		</td></tr>
		<tr>
		
